alwaysApply: true
---
# LANGUAGE
- Always communicate in Spanish (España) when speaking to the user.
- All identifiers (variables, functions, types, interfaces, components, filenames) must always use descriptive English names.
# DOCUMENTATION STYLE
- All documentation and comments must use **TSDoc** style.
- Every file should include a **file-level TSDoc header** explaining:
  - Purpose of the file.
  - Key exported entities.
  - Relevant types or variables used across the file.
- Only add inline TSDoc comments when a piece of logic truly requires clarification.
# COMMENT RESTRICTIONS
- Do NOT include meta-commentary such as:
  - “I changed this because…”
  - “This works better like this…”
  - “The AI decided to…”
- Only comment functional behavior, never the reasons behind code modifications.
- Comments must describe WHAT the code does, not WHY the AI wrote it.
# RESPECT EXISTING DOCUMENTATION
- If documentation already exists, DO NOT rewrite or overwrite it.
- Only update documentation when:
  - A variable, function or type name was changed.
  - A new export was added.
  - The logic changed in a way that the documentation becomes inaccurate.
# CODE STYLE
- Never add comments that restate what is obvious from the code itself.
- Avoid noise comments (“helper function”, “we return the value”, etc.).
- Keep code clean, elegant and minimalistic.
- Prefer explicit descriptive names instead of comments explaining bad naming.
# PRIORITIES WHEN EDITING CODE
1. Preserve existing structure.
2. Maintain or improve clarity.
3. Follow the naming conventions.
4. Update TSDoc headers only when needed.
# IF ASKED TO REFACTOR
- Apply transformations without adding meta-comments.
- Keep comments strictly functional and TSDoc-compliant.
- If a refactor changes the public interface, update the TSDoc header.